No, apparently not. The creature hissed and tried to fly directly at Thassalin. Luckily, Thassalin was agile enough despite his size and dodged, but Nyssi let out a scream when she almost lost her grip on Thassalin's smooth scales.
“HOW CAN WE KILL IT?”, Nyssi screamed.
“AIM FOR THEIR HEADS!”
“THIS WILL BE DIFFICULT!”
Thassalin hissed and then drew a circle, closer to the mountain he called home. The dark beast followed, but got slightly panicky when it was hit by a beam of fire from behind. It had not realized that it was no longer alone. It became even more panicky when Thassalin slowed down and then swung his tail against its head, throwing it off course.
Growling and snarling, it flew upward and spat into the air. Everything suddenly became dark, as if the monster had sucked the light from the sky and replaced it with a cloud of eternal night.
When he could suddenly see nothing anymore, Thassalin tried to retreat. He felt himself scraping along the tree branches before finally plunging into a clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen and shot directly toward him, dragging the black cloud with it.
“Kayel!”, Tenuk shouted as he slipped out of the cloud and began circling to look for Nyssi and Thassalin in the darkness below. “What should we do now, Kayel…? Kayel, where are you?”
Below, Nyssi struggled to her feet. She was sure she had broken something, but her strange, supernatural healing powers had already begun to take effect. Unfortunately, this was not the case for Thassalin. He leaned exhausted against the only tree that had not collapsed under his weight. Nyssi tried her best to get close to Thassalin, but she could hardly see more than two meters. Everything was pitch black and shrouded in eerie shadows. And in that shadow, something was screaming and screeching.
A terrifying, armored tail crashed next to Nyssi onto the ground and knocked her down. But she noticed that the tail was just wildly swinging and not intentionally trying to hit her. The beast, or rather, the little that Nyssi could see and hear of it, growled and swiped its claws at the shadows it had created. Something shot through the darkness, stabbed the monster, and confused it.
Suddenly, a gunshot cracked through the fog, and the monster fell silent, collapsed to the ground, and lay motionless. The darkness around them dissipated, and they saw what had happened: Kayel was standing on the beast, heavily breathing and holding his gun.
“That was… The craziest shadow leap I’ve ever made… Thanto kat’olon…,” Kabel gasped for breath. His eyes glowed almost black, and a dark energy swirled around his body. But as he was still speaking, color returned to his armor, and his eyes took on their normal yellow color again.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. They had all known that Kayel possessed these strange shadow powers. He rarely used them because most found them creepy and quite intimidating. But Nyssi hadn’t known that Kayel could also use these powers in any kind of darkness. And the way Kayel was behaving, he apparently was also quite surprised.
“Are you okay?”, Nyssi blurted out.
“Yes, I’m fine. I killed something, I’ll be back to normal in a moment.” Kayel examined his work as Tenuk flew down, landed next to him, and returned to his normal spastic form.
Now that the beast was no longer moving, they could see better what it was. Its skin was raven-black and slimy, but the slime remained firmly attached to its body. It had four wings and four extremities, all ending in long, thin claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what the hell they were looking at, something screeched and jumped out of a nearby bush. However, it did not reach them, because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, causing the monster to slide to a stop in front of Nyssi's feet. Nyssi didn't want to take any risks. She grabbed her shotgun, fired without thinking at its skull, and the creature died on the spot.
"Ups…," muttered Retvik from the driver's seat before he awkwardly turned off the engine and got out of the truck. "Uh, that was actually not intentional. Are you all okay?"
"You missed all the action," scolded Tenuk. "Where were you?"
"You all just left me standing there. I came as quickly as I could…," sighed Retvik. "May I ask what those terrible creatures are?"
Retvik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had managed to get back on his feet. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit dazed, but not seriously injured.
“YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTIIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. BEINGS THAT WERE WANDERING HERE WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS.”
“You mean the terrible god-monster thing that we… helped kill?”, stammered Tenuk.
“YES. EXACTLY THAT. THERE MIGHT BE MORE. BUT I COULD NOT SHOOT IN THE HEAD. I DON'T HAVE A GUN. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, OR?“ Thassalin limped over to Kayel and patted his head. “THANK YOU VERY MUCH, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST NOT SO MURDEROUS AND NOT SO GOOD AT KILLING WHOLE UNIVERSES.”
“Um… thank you… I guess…”, Kayel shrugged. “So, are we done here then?”
Nyssi shrugged. She grabbed her camera and took some photos of the now definitely dead beasts. Then she drew her favorite weapon, the ornate Death God dagger, and began cutting off one of the beast's horns. She then moved on to the second one. But as Nyssi was just finishing, the beasts suddenly burst into flames and transformed into a pile of ash in an instant. The same thing happened to the horns that Nyssi had cut off.
“So, that's simultaneously practical and impractical…,” Nyssi sighed. “But at least I have the photos, hopefully.”
